article.headline: McGrady scores 17 of his 43 in third quarter
article.linkText: McGrady tops 40 again as Magic beat Jazz
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Tracy McGrady demanded boos from Orlando's fans if the Magic gave another halfhearted effort. Then, his team went out and earned nothing but cheers. McGrady scored 17 of his 43 points in the third quarter for his second straight 40-point game, and Orlando snapped an eight-game losing streak with a 90-77 win over the Utah Jazz on Wednesday night. The Magic's defensive effort was a 50-point turnaround from Tuesday's 127-104 loss at Milwaukee. Orlando allowed 71 first-half points, and a fed-up McGrady blistered his teammates' "embarrassing" effort afterward. The team captain's tongue-lashing seemed to work, although McGrady wished it hadn't been necessary. "I can't do too much talking to the guys about what they need to do; it's too late for that," said McGrady, who also had eight rebounds and five assists. "So, what I've got to do is come out and take care of me, and hopefully they'll follow my lead. "Tonight, I had a few guys with me and we got the win." Juwan Howard added 20 points and nine rebounds, and Gordan Giricek had 15 points. Both players have been mentioned prominently in trade talks; the NBA's trading deadline is Thursday afternoon. "I hope this game was good enough to stay here," Giricek said after shooting 6-for-9 from the field and 2-of-4 from 3-point range. "We'll see." Orlando, the worst defensive team in the NBA, hadn't allowed fewer than 87 points since Nov. 3 -- a span of 52 games. This was only the sixth time this year the Magic gave up fewer than 90. The statistics during the losing streak were worse: 110 points allowed per game on 52-percent shooting. "We just wanted to come out and show that we had pride and that we want to play this game," Magic guard Keith Bogans said. "We're not going to just lay down and let people walk all over us." The Jazz, losers of three straight, shot 37.6 percent -- and it took a fourth-quarter burst to raise that mark. "We forgot what we were doing when we were trying to execute," said Jazz coach Jerry Sloan, who warned of lineup changes. "We got very selfish, and we got concerned about who was and who wasn't going to get the ball." During one 7{-minute stretch, beginning midway through the second quarter, the Jazz went scoreless while missing nine shots. Shortly after Utah found the basket, Howard's jumper gave Orlando a 42-31 lead with nine minutes left in the quarter. By comparison, Orlando allowed Milwaukee 37 points in the first quarter. "We responded from last night's fiasco and really showed a lot of pride tonight," Orlando coach Johnny Davis said. Carlos Arroyo led Utah with 14 points, and Andrei Kirilenko scored 12 on 5-for-18 shooting against McGrady's defense. Raul Lopez added 12 points and a career-high four steals. McGrady posted back-to-back 40-point games for the fifth time in his career. He scored 41 against the Bucks, seizing the lead in the NBA's scoring race from Philadelphia's Allen Iverson. McGrady made 13 of 31 shots and sank 14 of 15 free throws. "He's upped his game, and we need that from him every night," Davis said.

Game notes
Before Wednesday, the Magic had surrendered at least 60 first-half points in five of their last seven games. ... Shaquille O'Neal is the only other Magic player to post consecutive 40-point games in the regular season. He accomplished the feat in November 1994.
